issue_body:
I have a page in the templates/ folder that I'm serving to web requests. I'd like to have a separate stylesheet for the page. 

Here's what I've done:

```
# example_page.py
from will.plugin import WillPlugin
from will.decorators import respond_to, periodic, hear, randomly, route, rendered_template, require_settings
from bottle import static_file

class ExamplePlugin(WillPlugin):
    @route("/example_path")
    def example_path(self):
        context = {"foo": "bar"}
        return rendered_template("example.html", context)

# At the recommendation of other bottle-specific examples
@route('/static/<filename>')
def server_static(filename):
    return static_file(filename, root='/static')
```

And inside the root will dir, I have a folder called `static` which contains `style.css`

Inside of `templates/example.html` there's `<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/static/style.css">`


Now 2 things:

1. I'm not sure how to test if this works reliably (short of doing html and changing styles around I guess)
2. I don't know if there's a way easier way that I'm missing


Anyway, if I can explain this any better please let me know. Still new to this stuff, so please bear with me.

@arose 

from console
`pd.bond.toJSON is not a function`

Trying to convert XML to JSON using jsonxsl+xsltproc is failing when the data has an identityref with the prefix defined on the tag of the text.

For example, using following YANG modules:
```yang
module test {
  namespace "http://example.com/test";
  prefix t;

  import "test2" {
    prefix "t2";
  }

  container x {
    leaf y {
      type identityref {
        base "t2:dummy";
      }
    }
  }
}
```
```yang
module test2 {
  namespace "http://example.com/test2";
  prefix t2;
  identity dummy;
  identity alpha {
    base "dummy";
  }
}
```

Along with following data:
```xml
<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<data xmlns="urn:ietf:params:xml:ns:netconf:base:1.0">
  <x xmlns="http://example.com/test">
    <y xmlns:t2="http://example.com/test2">t2:alpha</y>
  </x>
</data>
```

Attempting to convert XML to JSON gives:
```bash
$ pyang -f jsonxsl -o test.xsl test.yang test2.yang
$ xsltproc test.xsl data.xml
Undefined namespace prefix: t2
{
  "test:x": {
```

yang2dsdl says that the data is valid:
```bash
$ yang2dsdl -t data -j -b test -v data.xml test.yang test2.yang
== Generating RELAX NG schema './test-data.rng'
Done.

== Generating Schematron schema './test-data.sch'
Done.

== Generating DSRL schema './test-data.dsrl'
Done.

== Validating grammar and datatypes ...
data.xml validates.

== Adding default values... done.

== Validating semantic constraints ...
No errors found.
```

I think the error is related to the level used for namespaces in jsonxsl-templates.xsl (line 270):
```
266     <xsl:variable name="modname">
267       <xsl:call-template name="nsuri-to-module">
268   <xsl:with-param
269       name="uri"
270       select="../namespace::*[name()=normalize-space($prf)]"/>
271       </xsl:call-template>
272     </xsl:variable>
```

It looks like select is using the parent's namespace information, so the newly defined prefix is not found

